DESCRIPTION
The retros repeatedly attribute wins/losses to model seats, but the durable distinction is review mode: spec adversary, runtime verifier, docs/reality checker, security/data-integrity checker. Refactor the gate prompt/runbook so roles are explicit and short, reducing dependence on a dense runbook and model personality.

DESIGN
## Plan

**Approach:** The retros credit gate wins/losses to model SEATS (codex caught X,
gemini missed Y), but the durable mechanism is the review LENS being applied
(spec adversary, runtime verifier, docs/reality checker, security/data-integrity
checker). Refactor `review-gate-runbook.md` to add ONE compact "Reviewer Roles"
section near the top that defines the role lenses and how seats map to them, and
re-anchor the prose so model identity reads as "which seat happens to fill a
lens" rather than "the model IS the quality mechanism." This is ADDITIVE
structure on top of the existing strict multi-seat-unanimity gate — no policy is
weakened. The dense per-seat caveats and P1-P4 disciplines are kept verbatim but
reframed as the RATIONALE/REFERENCE behind the compact roles, with the
recurring-defect classes (#1-#7) and Plan-Phase disciplines (P1-P4) explicitly
tagged with the role lens each one exercises so they read as worked examples of a
lens rather than free-floating prose.

**Naming guard (avoid schema collision):** the structured gate schema already
uses `reviewed_stages[].role` to mean the STAGE-ARTIFACT role
(`plan`/`diff`/`verify`) — see docs/gates.md:36 and
docs/plans/product/gate-reviewer-record-schema.md:200-201. That is a DIFFERENT
concept from the reviewer-lens roles introduced here. To prevent confusion the
new section is titled "Reviewer Roles (review lenses)" and uses the word "lens"
in running text; the plan adds an explicit one-line note that these lenses are
NOT the `reviewed_stages[].role` field and require NO schema change.

**Decision (must be made explicitly): roles are a CHECKLIST every seat applies,
NOT one-role-per-seat.** Adopt EVERY-SEAT-COVERS-ALL-LENSES. Rationale, grounded
in the runbook's own evidence:
- Multi-seat unanimity is preserved ONLY if every seat is adversarial across the
  whole surface; if we split one lens per seat we lose redundancy — a single
  seat's miss on its lens would have no second checker. Seats are the REDUNDANCY;
  lenses are the SHARED CHECKLIST each redundant seat runs.
- The runbook's strongest evidence is cross-lens: the inlined spec-focused seats
  (codex/gemini) repeatedly caught spec-completeness/adversarial-input defects
  the repo-aware Opus seat GO'd (runbook Recurring Defect Class #2,
  review-gate-runbook.md:561-596), and codex caught a runtime/cross-compile defect
  the darwin-only empirical seat missed (#7, :693-716). These show different SEATS
  are differently reliable at the SAME lens — which only works if every seat is
  asked to apply every lens, so the panel has multiple independent attempts per
  lens. Assigning one lens per seat would have SUPPRESSED exactly the catches the
  runbook documents.
- Therefore: lenses are the QUESTIONS every seat must answer; the multi-seat
  panel is the redundancy that makes a miss on any one lens unlikely. Seat
  sandbox realities (codex diff-only, Opus can mutation-test, gemini inlined)
  affect HOW a seat exercises a lens, not WHICH lenses it owns.

**The role taxonomy (4 lenses — compact, 1-2 lines + required evidence each):**

1. **Spec Adversary** — Charge: does the artifact satisfy the acceptance criteria
   AS WRITTEN, including every field/key of any struct it touches and every
   ambiguous criterion read literally? Hunt silently-dropped fields, convenient
   reinterpretations, and inputs the spec ALLOWS that bypass validation / spoof
   provenance / inject. Evidence: cite the acceptance line + the artifact
   line:col it satisfies or violates; for any struct, enumerate its fields and
   mark each covered/omitted.

2. **Runtime Verifier** — Charge: does it actually build, run, and pass — on the
   paths that matter, not just the host happy path? Includes cross-compile for
   platform APIs and constructing the input where a heuristic picks wrong.
   Evidence: the command run + observed result (or, for diff-only seats, the
   green-test summary trusted + an explicit "did not execute" note); for platform
   APIs, the `GOOS=… go build` result.

3. **Docs/Reality Checker** — Charge: do docs/claims match the code as it now is?
   No doc claims unshipped behavior; generated-doc blast radius is complete
   (every regenerated page, not just the obvious one); README/index usage stays
   consistent. Evidence: cite doc line vs code line; for generated artifacts,
   the full set of files the generator emits.

4. **Security / Data-Integrity Checker** — Charge: can this lose/corrupt data,
   break backward compat, or be abused? Reserved-key/`--ref`-override holes,
   round-trip byte-stability of optional blocks, absent-vs-present-null, refs/git
   plumbing safety. Evidence: the adversarial input tried + observed
   guard/behavior; for round-trip, the before/after bytes.

Each lens maps to existing runbook content so nothing is lost: Spec Adversary ←
Recurring Defect Class #2 + Plan-Phase P1/P3; Runtime Verifier ← #7 + P1
verify-the-verification; Docs/Reality ← #6 (generated blast radius) +
Epic-Close reconcile; Security/Data-Integrity ← #1 (reserved keys) + #5
(optional-block state model) + #3/#4 (guard-test rigor). P2 (premise-check /
BUILD-vs-DEFER) and P4 (artifact-creating beads vetted against all gates) are
cross-lens plan-phase gates and stay in their own short Plan-Phase block,
re-labelled as applying to ALL lenses.

**Seat→role mapping (no model-identity-as-mechanism):** add a short paragraph
stating "Any sufficiently capable reviewer can apply all four lenses; the gate's
strength is N independent seats EACH applying the full lens checklist, not any
one model. We currently seat codex (openai/gpt-5.5), gemini
(google/gemini-3.1-pro-preview), in-harness Opus (anthropic/claude-opus-4-7), and
pi/pilms (lmstudio/qwen) — each runs the SAME lens checklist; differences in seat
reliability per lens are why we keep multiple seats, not a reason to specialize
them." The existing per-seat sandbox caveats stay, retitled "Per-seat execution
constraints (how a seat applies the lenses)" so they read as mechanics, not as
the seat's identity/role.

**Role-specific prompt payload shape:** extend the existing single Reviewer
Prompt Template (review-gate-runbook.md:239-271) with ONE compact "Apply these
review lenses" block listing the four lenses as imperative bullets (each = the
1-line charge + "produce: <evidence>"). It is a single payload that ENUMERATES
the lenses (not four separate prompts), so it composes with the existing
seat-only framing, the GO/BLOCK return contract, and the EMPIRICAL-vs-REASONED
separation already in practice. Add a one-line note: a BLOCK must say WHICH lens
failed + the cited evidence, so disputed-claim re-verification (below) can target
that lens's evidence.

**How each PRESERVE-constraint is kept (additive, not replacement):**
- *Multi-seat unanimity* — UNCHANGED. Gate Weight tiers (Tier 1/2/3) and "every
  tier requires UNANIMOUS pass" (review-gate-runbook.md:13-55) are untouched;
  lenses are the per-seat checklist, seats remain the unanimity unit.
- *Disputed-claim verification* — UNCHANGED and reinforced. Result
  Classification's empirical-reproduction rule (:338-376) and the
  disproven-BLOCK handling stay verbatim; the prompt change makes BLOCKs cite a
  lens + evidence, which makes the re-verify step MORE targeted, not weaker.
- *Plan-Phase Discipline P1-P4* (:718-834) — kept verbatim; only re-tagged with
  the lens each exercises (P1→Runtime/Spec, P3→Spec, P2+P4→cross-lens). The
  hard-won rationale and `etude-…` worked examples are NOT deleted.
- *Risk tiers* — UNCHANGED (Gate Weight section untouched).
- *Degraded-gate fallback* — UNCHANGED (Degraded Gate Policy :393-436 untouched;
  a disregarded seat is still a TOOLING outage, orthogonal to lenses).
- *Structured gate-record capture* — UNCHANGED (`etude capture-gate`,
  capture-conventions :898-979 untouched). Explicit note: the new lenses do NOT
  add a schema field and are NOT the `reviewed_stages[].role` field.

**Reduce load (the actual goal) — what becomes active vs reference:** the COMPACT
ACTIVE layer is (a) the new four-lens checklist section + (b) the one lens block
in the prompt template. Everything else (per-seat caveats, the seven Recurring
Defect Classes, P1-P4 with their worked examples, Degraded Gate Policy, capture
conventions) is reframed as RATIONALE/REFERENCE that backs the lenses — left in
place, cross-referenced FROM the compact section ("each lens is exercised by the
defect classes / disciplines below"), not duplicated. 8hq.6 does NOT itself move
rules into scripts or shrink the runbook body — it adds the role spine and
re-labels existing content.

**8hq.6 / 8hq.7 boundary (so they don't collide):**
- 8hq.6 (this bead) = define the reviewer-role LENSES + seat→role mapping +
  prompt-payload lens block; reframe existing prose as lens rationale. It writes
  the role taxonomy that 8hq.7 will later reference. It does NOT create
  checklists/commands or compress the runbook body.
- 8hq.7 = COMPRESS the high-frequency close/gate/capture rules into short
  executable checklists/commands, leaving the long runbook as reference. 8hq.7
  may point its gate-execution checklist AT the lens block 8hq.6 creates.
- Stated in the plan so a 8hq.7 implementer knows the lens section is the
  authoritative role source and should be referenced, not re-derived.

**Files (docs-only, no Go/script changes):**
- `docs/plans/dogfood/review-gate-runbook.md` — PRIMARY. Add "Reviewer Roles
  (review lenses)" section (after Purpose / before or alongside Gate Weight);
  add the lens block to the Reviewer Prompt Template; retitle the per-seat
  caveats as execution constraints; add the seat→role mapping paragraph; re-tag
  P1-P4 and Recurring Defect Classes #1-#7 with their lens (light inline labels,
